Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Challenges - 1", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8203160857509995`*^9, 
  3.820316089567793*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a76596cd-33bc-4470-b6f9-\
86b941d2b3f6"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["BAR CHARTS:",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8203161817669573`*^9, 3.820316183302856*^9}, 
   3.8203162546709895`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"78ea3d3c-10e6-4146-bb93-\
9a49c0c4a2cd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Make a (horizontal) bar chart showing the GDP per capita of all countries \
in South America. Hints: ",
 StyleBox["CountryData[\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]SouthAmerica\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " returns a list of all countries in South America; ",
 StyleBox["CountryData[country, \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]GDPPerCapita\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " returns the GDP per capita of a country; "
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.78766146270336*^9, 3.787661509848934*^9}, {
  3.787661551840349*^9, 3.787661585200135*^9}, {3.787661731930229*^9, 
  3.787661778552841*^9}, {3.787662201357724*^9, 3.787662255898539*^9}, {
  3.7876623548335133`*^9, 
  3.78766235483425*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1343562c-7b3f-4158-b23b-\
d8b7e563d879"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "You want to compare male and female life expectancies for different \
countries. What chart would you make? Create a function that accepts a list \
of countries as an argument, and makes the appropriate plot. Test it with a \
list of some countries, maybe the same countries we used as examples in the \
notebook. Can you draw any conclusion from the plot? Hint: The command ",
 StyleBox["CountryData[\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Properties\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " lists all the quantities that you can get with ",
 StyleBox["CountryData",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". "
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.78766146270336*^9, 3.787661509848934*^9}, {
  3.787661551840349*^9, 3.787661585200135*^9}, {3.787661731930229*^9, 
  3.787661778552841*^9}, {3.787662201357724*^9, 3.787662255898539*^9}, {
  3.787662537764061*^9, 3.78766275302776*^9}, {3.7876635398863792`*^9, 
  3.787663591949923*^9}, {3.7876638838945227`*^9, 3.78766393870361*^9}, {
  3.7876662255088882`*^9, 3.787666229570045*^9}, {3.7878335498510056`*^9, 
  3.7878335498510056`*^9}, {3.8203180077095385`*^9, 
  3.8203180225653725`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"02434586-a5d7-4ae3-8e5d-\
8ac7d1a2b20c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "Create a single-bar stacked bar chart depicting the distribution of the UK \
population according to city size, dividing cities into four categories: huge \
(cities with population above one million); large (population above 100,000 \
but below one million); small (population between 10,000 and 100,000); and \
tiny (population below 10,000). The bars represent the total number of people \
in the UK living in huge, large, small and tiny cities. \
\[LineSeparator]Hints: ",
 StyleBox["CityData[{All,\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]UnitedKingdom\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]}]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " returns the list of all UK cities in the database. ",
 StyleBox["CityData[city,\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]Population\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " returns the population of a given city; the population data may be \
missing, so you should discard results that match the ",
 StyleBox["_Missing",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " pattern. The result will be in the form ",
 StyleBox["Quantity[population, People]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ", so you should use the function ",
 StyleBox["QuantityMagnitude",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " to get just the population."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787682244065858*^9, 3.787682275553687*^9}, {
  3.7876823068978376`*^9, 3.7876825221301775`*^9}, {3.787682567390065*^9, 
  3.7876826800350084`*^9}, {3.7876827102901025`*^9, 3.7876828540823345`*^9}, {
  3.7876840548172555`*^9, 
  3.7876840548182526`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"47e6de49-6139-4a58-941d-\
60cfc0b13108"],

Cell[BoxData[
 StyleBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"cities", " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{"CityData", "[", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"All", ",", "\"\<UnitedKingdom\>\""}], "}"}], "]"}]}], ";"}],
  FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787904307134544*^9, 3.78790431722151*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[68]:=",ExpressionUUID->"934f1299-b955-496d-9348-ec3e4a857616"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"pops", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Map", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"CityData", "[", 
       RowBox[{"#", ",", " ", "\"\<Population\>\""}], "]"}], "&"}], ",", " ", 
     "cities"}], "]"}]}], ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787904389404217*^9, 3.787904421272416*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[69]:=",ExpressionUUID->"891a5c5e-b045-436c-a334-7b648be4b618"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
Define a function that accepts the name of a country as an argument, and \
returns a list with the total number of people in that country living in \
huge, large, small and tiny cities. Use this function to generate single-bar \
stacked bar charts for a few countries, for example France and South Africa.\
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787682244065858*^9, 3.787682275553687*^9}, {
  3.7876823068978376`*^9, 3.7876825221301775`*^9}, {3.787682567390065*^9, 
  3.7876826800350084`*^9}, {3.7876827102901025`*^9, 3.7876828540823345`*^9}, {
  3.7876840595316486`*^9, 3.7876842115211296`*^9}, {3.787685652165682*^9, 
  3.7876856521666794`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"99e3714a-2baa-47ef-8a95-\
b84d7c83346d"],

Cell["\<\
Using the function you defined above, create a function that accepts a list \
of countries, and generates a percentile stacked bar chart depicting the \
fraction of the population living in huge, large, small and tiny cities.\
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787682244065858*^9, 3.787682275553687*^9}, {
  3.7876823068978376`*^9, 3.7876825221301775`*^9}, {3.787682567390065*^9, 
  3.7876826800350084`*^9}, {3.7876827102901025`*^9, 3.7876828540823345`*^9}, {
  3.7876840595316486`*^9, 3.7876842115211296`*^9}, {3.787685659152*^9, 
  3.787685777464654*^9}, {3.78783363352798*^9, 
  3.78783363352798*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"de56b341-8a15-4f87-873a-\
9ec80105015f"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["SCATTER PLOTS:",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8203162473906326`*^9, 
  3.8203162509592624`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a37667ea-e602-4024-bde6-\
1643e7111709"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "What quantities do you expect will correlate with a country's life \
expectancy? Inspect the quantities in ",
 StyleBox["CountryData[\"Properties\"]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and choose a few that you expect to be strongly correlated to life \
expectancy. Create scatter plots to test your ideas."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787976253475358*^9, 3.7879762662921*^9}, {
  3.7879764242776814`*^9, 3.7879764298010616`*^9}, {3.787976550902897*^9, 
  3.787976550904892*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8ed2310c-8ed7-4a5c-b6fb-\
886ca4954237"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Create a function ",
 StyleBox["mfDiff",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " that accepts a ",
 StyleBox["CountryData",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\[CloseCurlyQuote]s property (such as \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]LiteracyFraction\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] or \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]GDPPerCapita\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]) as an argument, \
and plots a scatter data of that property versus the difference in life \
expectancies between females and males for all countries. So\[LineSeparator]",
 StyleBox["mfDiff[\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]GDPPerCapita\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]]\
 ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "creates a scatter plot of GDP per capita versus the difference in \
male/female life expectancies."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787976253475358*^9, 3.7879762662921*^9}, {
  3.7879764242776814`*^9, 3.7879764298010616`*^9}, {3.78797655201196*^9, 
  3.787976710457003*^9}, {3.787976741748265*^9, 3.787976744340335*^9}, {
  3.78797682293182*^9, 3.7879768491642284`*^9}, {3.7879873512759438`*^9, 
  3.787987447897211*^9}, {3.8203183925584407`*^9, 
  3.8203183931839347`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"94a73456-541e-40d0-8ba2-\
8d51fb9a6dbc"],

Cell["\<\
Create a function that accepts a year as an argument, and plots a scatter \
plot of population versus GDP per capita for all countries at that year.\
\>", "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.787976253475358*^9, 3.7879762662921*^9}, {
  3.7879764242776814`*^9, 3.7879764298010616`*^9}, {3.78797655201196*^9, 
  3.787976714916087*^9}, {3.787976780051691*^9, 3.7879768457962356`*^9}, {
  3.787982487340979*^9, 3.787982491124001*^9}, {3.820316265543055*^9, 
  3.820316267553808*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c42cb308-561b-45a9-9792-\
1c167c031d05"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the first notebook, we defined a function ",
 StyleBox["countryPlot",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " that accepts the names of two ",
 StyleBox["CountryData",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " properties as arguments, and displays a scatter plot of those properties \
for all countries in Mathematica\[CloseCurlyQuote]s database. Change this \
function to make it accept a continent as its third argument. The countries \
of that continent should be shown as points of a different colour from the \
other countries."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7879771786840115`*^9, 3.787977223928288*^9}, {
  3.7879772566140933`*^9, 3.7879772566140933`*^9}, {3.787977290458702*^9, 
  3.787977380972024*^9}, {3.820318880037261*^9, 3.820318937469016*^9}, {
  3.8203189929165525`*^9, 
  3.82031909378872*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3f6b59fb-fcab-4127-a44f-\
9e5760aa5cf3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Modify ",
 StyleBox["countryPlot",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " so that when the mouse hovers over it, a tooltip showing the country's \
name shows up."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7879771786840115`*^9, 
  3.787977223928288*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e3277282-d4b3-4492-9706-\
3a38aee98f39"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Change ",
 StyleBox["countryPlot",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " so that the tooltip shows the country\[CloseCurlyQuote]s flag instead of \
its name."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7879771786840115`*^9, 
  3.7879772534355936`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3b5318da-b1e0-44aa-a326-\
3968e5f60f8a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Modify ",
 StyleBox["countryPlot",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " so that when the mouse hovers over it, a tooltip showing a table with \
relevant information about the country shows up. Information on the table \
could include the country's name, its capital city, its population, its \
continent, etc."
}], "ItemNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.7879771786840115`*^9, {3.7879773987953453`*^9, 3.787977400640029*^9}, {
   3.820316332945463*^9, 
   3.8203163329464855`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"928a29ac-2343-435f-bbdd-\
4aa23416267c"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["Ignore this problem",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "ItemNumbered",
